W2. The paper lacks experimental comparison with the most directly related concurrent work.

The paper claims FreshPER is "the first work to successfully apply PER to LLM/VLM reinforcement learning," yet provides no experimental comparison against the following concurrent works:

Zhang, Hongzhi, et al. "RLEP: Reinforcement Learning with Experience Replay for LLM Reasoning."
Fatemi, Mehdi. "Prioritized Replay for RL Post-training."
RLEP was publicly available well before any reasonable ECCV 2026 submission deadline. Without these comparisons, the paper's core novelty claim cannot be independently verified.

W3. The staleness of advantage estimates is not discussed.

The advantage estimate 
 is computed at trajectory collection time and stored fixed in the replay buffer, never updated as the policy evolves. As training progresses, the policy's value landscape shifts, and stale advantage estimates may produce misleading gradient directions. This issue is entirely absent from the paper. The ESS analysis addresses the decay of sample weights but does not touch the validity of the advantage estimates themselves.

W4. The training paradigm is inconsistently characterized.

The paper's contribution statement describes the method as "a complete off-policy training pipeline," yet Algorithm 1 clearly shows that each iteration consists of both an on-policy update step (Lines 1–5) and off-policy replay updates (Lines 7–11), making it a hybrid on/off-policy scheme. Furthermore, the Introduction devotes most of its text to motivating the limitations of on-policy RL, then abruptly introduces an off-policy solution in the contributions, leaving a conspicuous logical gap.

Minor Weaknesses:
W5. The VLM contribution is weak.

Only two of the eight evaluation tasks involve vision (FrozenLake VLM and GeoQA). The gain on GeoQA is merely +1.3% (0.475 → 0.481). The method's applicability to multimodal settings is asserted rather than demonstrated.

W6. Presentation and citation issues.

Two evaluation benchmarks have citation problems: AIME lacks any specification of the problem source, year range, or subset used (lines 292–294), making the experimental setup unreproducible; GeoQA (Chen J, Tang J, Qin J, et al. "GeoQA: A Geometric Question Answering Benchmark Towards Multimodal Numerical Reasoning") is a published benchmark that is not cited anywhere in the paper.

W7. The benchmark selection is misaligned with the paper's core motivation.

The paper motivates FreshPER primarily through the high cost of agentic RL data collection, yet only one of the eight evaluated tasks (NQ Search) involves genuine multi-turn tool use. The remaining tasks are either toy grid-world navigation environments or pure reasoning tasks with no environment interaction, which is insufficient to support the central claim that FreshPER meaningfully reduces agentic data collection costs. If the method's core value lies in reducing expensive agentic collection overhead, validation on more representative agentic settings — such as code execution or multi-tool coordination — is needed.

