The main contribution of this paper is a new replay prioritization mechanism, supported by theoretical motivation and empirical evaluation. Therefore, I think the novelty is mainly methodological.

Paper Summary:
This paper proposes a new experience replay method for LLM/VLM reinforcement learning. The authors argue that on-policy RL uses each trajectory only once, which is wasteful in multi-turn agentic settings, and that standard replay methods fail because priorities become stale as the policy changes rapidly. To address this, they propose FreshPER, motivated by an ESS-based argument, and integrate it into an off-policy training pipeline on top of ROLL. Experiments on 0.5B, 3B, and 7B models show that the method performs better than both on-policy training and standard PER.

Paper Strengths:
The problem the paper focuses on is important: how to improve the data reuse mechanism in expensive multi-turn LLM/VLM RL settings.

The method is simple and well motivated. The failure mode of standard PER that they identify is convincing, and the freshness-aware decay they propose is a clean fix.

The experimental results are broad and strong. Standard PER performs poorly, while FreshPER shows better performance than both on-policy training and standard PER.

The ablations on (\tau) and IS correction are useful.

Major Weaknesses:
The motivation mainly comes from sample efficiency and expensive interaction, but the evaluation focuses more on peak performance than on fixed interaction budgets, rollout budgets, or wall-clock savings. If these aspects are added, the paper would be better validated.

The baselines are somewhat limited. The paper lacks comparisons with stronger replay/off-policy baselines beyond on-policy training and standard PER.

The theoretical motivation is still heuristic at an important step, since policy divergence is approximated through elapsed gradient steps and absorbed into the tunable hyperparameter (\tau). The ablations also suggest nontrivial sensitivity to this choice.

Minor Weaknesses:
The paper would benefit from reporting fixed-budget results in the main paper.

The empirical validation is mainly on REINFORCE++, so generality to PPO/GRPO-style setups is argued more than demonstrated.

Preliminary Recommendation: 4: Borderline Accept
Justification Of Preliminary Recommendation:
The problem the paper focuses on is important, the proposed method is simple and well motivated, and the experimental results are positive. FreshPER shows convincingly better performance than standard PER. Overall, I see this as a borderline-accept paper with a clean and useful contribution.

Suggestions For Rebuttal:
Please report at least one fixed interaction budget or fixed rollout budget comparison.

Please compare against at least one stronger replay/off-policy baseline beyond standard PER.

Please clarify how sensitive performance is to (\tau), and whether a simple tuning heuristic works across tasks.

