This paper proposes an extension of widely-used priority experience replay, which is a general algorithm design for reinforcement learning rather than a specific application.

Paper Summary:
The paper says that reinforcement learning for LLMs and VLMs is currently very wasteful because popular on-policy methods use each collected trajectory only once, which is especially costly for multi-step agent tasks, and it introduces FreshPER as a way to safely reuse old experience. The key idea is that standard prioritized experience replay fails for large models because their policies change so quickly that trajectories that once looked highly useful become stale, yet ordinary PER keeps oversampling them; FreshPER fixes this by multiplying the replay priority by an exponential age-decay term so older samples gradually become less likely to be reused.

Paper Strengths:
It tackles an important practical problem: post-training RL for LLMs/VLMs is sample-inefficient because expensive trajectories are usually used once and discarded.
The method is well motivated, not just empirically but also by an effective-sample-size argument tying policy drift to an exponential loss of usefulness in older data.
It is easy to plug into an existing replay pipeline: the paper presents FreshPER as a lightweight modification to PER rather than a whole new RL algorithm.
The empirical story is clean: standard PER often hurts, while FreshPER improves performance, which strongly supports the paper’s central claim that “freshness” is the missing ingredient.
Major Weaknesses:
The theoretical justification is only partial. The key step approximates policy divergence as proportional to elapsed gradient steps, which is reasonable but still heuristic rather than a tight adaptive estimate. The connection between (12) and (13) is loose.
The experimental setup appears limited to REINFORCE++, even though the paper frames FreshPER as broadly compatible with PER-style priorities; that leaves open how well it transfers to PPO, GRPO, or other common post-training algorithms.
SOTA algorithms in those evaluation benchmarks are not involved as baselines.
Some evaluation tasks are relatively controlled or synthetic, such as gridworld-style environments.
Error bounds were not provided.
